         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">15/5/86. ¶  ¶ In response to your last kind letter, honored Sir, let me first say, that I hope to unite the descriptions of the new Australian plants, published during the last few years, into a syste...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">86.05.15</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Alphonse de Candolle</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Bibliothèque des Conservatoire et Jardin botaniques, Geneva.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">15/5/86.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In response to your last kind letter, honored Sir, let me first say, that I hope to unite the descriptions of the new Australian plants, published during the last few years, into a systematic arrangement for the 12th vol. of the fragmenta, which work for various reasons came to a stand still.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No further parts of the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Fragmenta</seg> were issued after vol. 12, part 1, published in 1882 (B82.12.03).</p>
               </note> Meanwhile these scattered diagnoses are referred to in the supplements of the "Census", which I dedicated to you;<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M dedicated the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Census</seg> (B82.13.16) to George Bentham, Joseph Hooker and Alphonse de Candolle.</p>
               </note> the 3th (for 1885)<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B86.06.03.</p>
               </note> is soon to appear, as it is in the printers hands The New Guinean plants I collect into the special publication "Papuan plants", of which I send you the 8th part by this mail.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B86.03.02.</p>
               </note> In reference to the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">text </hi>
               </seg>of the <name key="Myoporinae">Myoporinae</name>,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The plates of this work (B86.06.05) were issued as ‘Volume II: Lithograms’. No Volume 1 containing text was issued.</p>
               </note> I would willingly in 1887 furnish <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">diagnoses</hi>
               </seg> and <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">descriptions</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">in latin</hi>
               </seg> for your "monographiae phanerogamorum", and I could add myself the few extra-australian species, so that the whole would be a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">perfect monography</hi>
               </seg> of the order. In 1888 or later (if God will continue my life mercifully so long) I should write the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">text</hi>
               </seg> for the plate separately in <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">English</hi>
               </seg>, so that my contribution to your monographiae would for ever be an original one. Having used the syst. veg. vol. I &amp; II &amp; the prodromus of your illustrious father and yourself since 1840, I should like very much to enjoy the honor yet in life of having contributed to these <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">standard</hi>
               </seg>-series of modern phytography by elaborating the <name key="Myoporinae">Myoporinae</name>, to which <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">not</hi>
               </seg> likely any future important additions will be made.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The contribution that M proposed for de Candolle’s series was never published.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If I treat the <name key="Myoporinae">Myoporinae</name> similarly to your elaboration of the <name key="Smilacinae">Smilacinae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A de </seg>Candolle (1878)</p>
               </note> and your excellent sons <name key="Meliaceae">Meliaceae</name>,<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>C. de </seg>Candolle (1878-96), vol. 1, 399-752.</p>
               </note> my whole text in latin would occupy only about 40 pages, so the <name key="Myoporinae">Myoporinae</name> could perhaps yet be included in the second part of vol. V of your Monographiae after the <name key="Amphelideae">Amphelideae</name> of our industrious friend Planchon.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Planchon (1887).</p>
               </note> I can attend to the extra-australian <name key="Myoporinae">Myoporinae</name> also, having sufficient material for the purpose here; but my illustrations here will be limited to Austral. species.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am now preparing a series of plates of <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>s, i.e. such species as have hitherto not yet been delineated.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Published as B87.13.04.</p>
               </note> This will facilitate the recognition of the numerous specific forms in this great genus for all times.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You write with an untrembling hand and with such mental force, that I presume your health remains firm and your eyesight unimpaired.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>May you thus long be spared, to guide efforts also in future for our favorite science.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I still think, that finally the genus <name key="Stylidium">Stylidium</name> will become <name key="Candollea">Candollea</name> everywhere, as we must have an important genus, to be a worthy monument for your great family name in bot science.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Amphelideae">Amphelideae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Candollea">Candollea</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Cinchona">Cinchona</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Meliaceae">Meliaceae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Myoporinae">Myoporinae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Smilacinae">Smilacinae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Stylidium">Stylidium</name>
            </p>
         </div>
